    <methods>
      <methodStep>
        <description>
          <section>
            <title>Research Methods:</title>
            <para>
              <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                  <para>Owing to significant misclassifications and omissions of official GIS layers from local and state agencies, two published land cover data sets were employed to estimate the number and areal extent of artificial lakes. Data sets include:</para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                  <para>(1) an ASTER-derived land cover classification [Land cover classification using Landsat Enhanced Thematic Mapper (ETM) data - year 2000 (http://caplter.asu.edu/data/data-catalog/?id=372)], and</para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                  <para>(2) a LANDSAT ETM-derived classification [Land cover classification using ASTER data - year 2000 (http://caplter.asu.edu/data/data-catalog/?id=250)].</para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                  <para>An amalgamation of the two data sets was required as the higher-resolution ASTER-derived data did not cover the entire study area.  Each data set includes a category for water. Areas with slope &gt;10% were omitted to remove mountain shadows mistakenly classified as water, and areas classified as water near the airport and downtown business district were removed. The analysis does not include the Salt and Verde River floodplains, except Tempe Town Lake, an artificial lake constructed in 1999. Because the data sets are derived from satellite images, single water bodies can be divided into discrete units by bridges. To address this and estimate the number of unique water bodies, individual lakes were merged over a range of buffers from 10 to 50 m. Results, discussion, and additional details are available in document DOI 10.1007/s11252-011-0208-1.</para>
                </listitem>
              </itemizedlist>
            </para>
          </section>
        </description>
      </methodStep>
    </methods>
